00:08:28.840 --> 00:08:31.780
We saw, for example,
in tournament species,

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:35.500
tournament species where you
have high levels of aggression

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:38.950
among males, male-male
competition for access

00:08:38.950 --> 00:08:39.880
to females.

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:42.780
As a result, males tend to
be a lot bigger than females.

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:45.610
They are being selected
for muscle mass,

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:48.950
secondary sexual
characteristics, plumage,

00:08:48.950 --> 00:08:51.880
big sharp canines for
slashing the other guy.

00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:55.200
Bringing up this issue of,
in a tournament species,

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:57.250
who does the male
want to mate with?

00:08:57.250 --> 00:09:00.300
What sort of female are males
interested in mating with?

00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:01.870
The answer being,
anyone who will

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:05.030
mate with them because
there's like no cost involved.

00:09:05.030 --> 00:09:08.440
All that's involved is no
parental behavior, none

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:10.190
of that, the cost of sperm.

00:09:10.190 --> 00:09:13.020
And literally, people
analyze the relative cost

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:16.260
of sperm versus eggs
in tournament species.

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:20.510
Males are dramatically un-choosy
as to who they mate with.

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:23.990
In tournament species, males
have dramatic variability

00:09:23.990 --> 00:09:27.130
in reproductive
success-- 5% accounting

00:09:27.130 --> 00:09:29.240
for 95% of the matings.

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:31.740
Female choice in a
tournament species.

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:33.620
What does a female
want out of a male?

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:36.140
She certainly is not going
to get good fatherhood out

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:36.650
of the guy.

00:09:36.650 --> 00:09:38.850
All she wants are good
genes because that's

00:09:38.850 --> 00:09:40.810
all she could hope
for from the guy.

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:43.430
A whole world of
female selectivity

00:09:43.430 --> 00:09:46.060
for markers of good genes.

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:48.360
And as we'll see in the
sexual behavior lectures,

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:52.040
a whole world of males
trying to fake out females

00:09:52.040 --> 00:09:53.900
across the animal
world, suggesting they

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:56.500
got better genes than
they actually do.

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.180
So we will come to that.

00:09:58.180 --> 00:09:59.620
Then tournament species.

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:02.009
Do you see female
abandonment of kids?

00:10:02.009 --> 00:10:04.050
Absolutely not, because
there's nobody else who's

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:05.340
going to take care of them.

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:07.750
Coupled with that,
you see single births

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:09.830
among those species, low level.

00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:12.150
High levels of aggression
amongst the males,

00:10:12.150 --> 00:10:13.810
low levels of parenting.

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:16.910
And males tend to live a
lot shorter than females.

00:10:16.910 --> 00:10:18.330
And what we saw
at the other end,

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:22.320
the pair-bonded species was a
completely different picture.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:24.590
Males are being
careful who they're

00:10:24.590 --> 00:10:27.752
mating with because the
wiring there is you mate,

00:10:27.752 --> 00:10:29.400
you take care of the kids.

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:31.560
